# Contributing to {{ProjectName}}

## Pull request titles drive releases

This repository uses Conventional Commits and validates pull request titles with
`.github/workflows/conventional-commits.yml`.

Use titles like:

- `feat: add order export endpoint`
- `fix(api): reject duplicate email addresses`
- `docs: clarify local setup`
- `refactor!: simplify the authentication pipeline`

Use `!` or a `BREAKING CHANGE:` footer in the merged commit when a change should
trigger a major version bump.

## Preferred merge flow

- Prefer **Squash and merge** so the pull request title becomes the commit that
  lands on `main`.
- In repository settings, turn on **Default to PR title for squash merge
  commits**.
- Keep the PR title stable once CI passes, because Release Please uses merged
  commit history to calculate the next version and changelog.

## Release automation

- `.github/workflows/release-please.yml` watches `main` and `master`.
- `release-please-config.json` defines the changelog sections and versioning
  behavior.
- `version.txt`, `CHANGELOG.md`, and `.release-please-manifest.json` are the
  release-state files that evolve over time.
- `docs/RELEASE.md` explains the full release flow plus the optional
  static-analysis setup.

## Local validation

Run the same baseline checks as CI before opening a pull request:

```powershell
dotnet restore .\{{ProjectName}}.slnx
dotnet format .\{{ProjectName}}.slnx --verify-no-changes --no-restore
dotnet build .\{{ProjectName}}.slnx --no-restore --configuration Release -p:TreatWarningsAsErrors=true
dotnet test .\{{ProjectName}}.slnx --no-build --configuration Release --collect:"XPlat Code Coverage" --results-directory .\.artifacts\test-results
```

See [`docs/SETUP.md`](docs/SETUP.md) for the complete day-to-day setup and
validation guidance.
